780
01:08:42,000 --> 01:08:54,000
But there's more of like with Siddhartha, there's more almost like a Buddhist sort of like watch the river and become the river.

781
01:08:54,000 --> 01:09:00,000
This kind of idea that what it means to truly experience the moment.

782
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:05,000
There is an experiential part of existentialism where you want to, it's not just about,

783
01:09:05,000 --> 01:09:11,000
we've been talking about kind of decisions and actions, but also what it means to listen, like you said, from Nietzsche.

784
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:16,000
Like what it means to really take in the world and experience the moment.

785
01:09:16,000 --> 01:09:23,000
So he's very good at writing about what it means to experience the moment and experience the full absurdity of the moment.

786
01:09:23,000 --> 01:09:30,000
And for him, I'm starting to forget, Steppenwolf I think is humor.

787
01:09:30,000 --> 01:09:37,000
It's part of the absurdity, which I think modern day internet explores very well with memes and so on.

788
01:09:37,000 --> 01:09:45,000
Humor is a fundamental part of the existentialist ethic that's able to deal with absurdity.

789
01:09:45,000 --> 01:09:48,000
You got to like laugh at it.

790
01:09:48,000 --> 01:09:52,000
I think there is some, let me just say something about humor because I think you're absolutely right.

791
01:09:52,000 --> 01:10:01,000
Kierkegaard, who is Danish and most people think deeply depressed and then so on, is actually an incredibly funny writer.

792
01:10:01,000 --> 01:10:09,000
And someone who was a classmate of mine in graduate school who left philosophy to become a Hollywood comedy writer.

793
01:10:09,000 --> 01:10:11,000
He's a very successful guy.

794
01:10:11,000 --> 01:10:15,000
And then he came back 25 years later and wrote, finished his dissertation.

795
01:10:15,000 --> 01:10:18,000
And I was the reader on the dissertation.

796
01:10:18,000 --> 01:10:21,000
There may be a conflict of interest, I'm not quite sure.

797
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:28,000
But his dissertation was about, he called it Kierkegaard and the funny, which is kind of a funny title.

798
01:10:28,000 --> 01:10:29,000
Yeah.

799
01:10:29,000 --> 01:10:40,000
But Kierkegaard, according to Eric Kaplan's reading, Kierkegaard does have this idea that there's something destabilizing about humor

800
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:48,000
that's crucial to the sort of the important possibilities for us.

801
01:10:48,000 --> 01:10:59,000
And so there's the idea that there's a moment when a joke is being set up, when you're sort of proceeding as if you're on stable ground.

802
01:10:59,000 --> 01:11:04,000
And then the punchline comes and the rug is pulled out from under you.

803
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:07,000
And for a moment, it's like you're falling.

804
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:17,000
There's nothing supporting you until you're captured by your totally new understanding of what was going on.

805
01:11:17,000 --> 01:11:23,000
And that humor necessarily has that kind of destabilizing feature to it.

806
01:11:23,000 --> 01:11:25,000
And that's like the riskiness.

807
01:11:25,000 --> 01:11:28,000
That's like the riskiness that you were pointing to.

808
01:11:28,000 --> 01:11:35,000
If there aren't risks in your life, if your life is totally safe, then there's no possibility of significance.

809
01:11:35,000 --> 01:11:45,000
And so I think on Eric's reading, Kierkegaard sort of wants to line up the importance of the riskiness and vulnerability in your life to its having meaning

810
01:11:45,000 --> 01:11:54,000
with the experience of destabilization that you get in jokes and comedy, which then becomes significant.

811
01:11:54,000 --> 01:12:00,000
When you remember having heard a joke for the first time, it's got a kind of salience for you.

